view.name: Infant Mortality by Race/Ethnicity, 2004-2013
view.description: This dataset is for infant mortality for 2004 through 2013. The death of a baby before his or her first birthday is called infant mortality. The dataset also includes California live birth population data that can be used to determine infant mortality rates. The infant mortality rate is an estimate of the number of infant deaths for every 1,000 live births. Race and Ethnicity of the infant is determined by the mother. As with any statistic, a rate based upon a small numerator and a much larger denominator may not be reliable.

columns.name: Age at death
columns.description: Neonatal deaths are deaths less than 28 days old.  Postneonatal deaths are deaths at least 28 days old and less than 1 year old.

columns.name: Rate
columns.description: per 1,000 live births in the calendar year.

Narrative Information.Description: The following are description of categories for the Open Data Portal infant mortality dataset: RACE and ETHNICITY.  The race and ethnicity categories for this dataset are tabulated using the following race and ethnic groups: American Indian, Asian, Black, Hispanic, Pacific Islander, White/Other, Two or More Races, and Not Stated and Unknown.  Members of Hispanic origin are determined first and include the ethnic groups of Mexican/Mexican-American/Chicano, Puerto Rican, Cuban, Central/South American, and Other Spanish/Hispanic. All other members are then determined to be Non-Hispanic.  Second, from the Non-Hispanic members, the members of the Two or More Races group are determined and are not reported in single race categories. The single race and ethnic categories are defined as follows: “American Indian” category includes Aleut, American Indian, and Eskimo; “Asian” category includes Asian Indian, Asian (specified/unspecified), Cambodian, Chinese, Filipino, Hmong, Japanese, Korean, Laotian, Thai, and Vietnamese; “Black” category includes members having origins in any of the black racial groups of Africa; “Hispanic” category.  Please see definition above. “Pacific Islander” category includes Guamanian, Hawaiian, Samoan, and Other Pacific Islander; “White” category includes White and Other (specified); “Two or More Races” category includes members who identify themselves as belonging to multiple-race categories; “Not Stated and Unknown” category includes members who declined to state a race or members for whom the race is unknown. GENDER: “Males” include births with gender of child not reported. California Department of Public Health data can be found on the departmental website at:  http://www.cdph.ca.gov/data and http://www.cdph.ca.gov/data/statistics/Pages/InfantDeathDataTables.aspx
